SSH_KEYS
Step 1: Check for Existing SSH Keys
Open your terminal (Git Bash on Windows) and check for existing keys with the following command:
ls -al ~/.ssh
Look for files named id_rsa.pub or id_ed25519.pub. If you see these files, you can skip to Step 3.

Step 2: Generate a New SSH Key
If you don't have an existing key, generate a new one using the recommended Ed25519 algorithm.
Run
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your_email@example.com" in your terminal, using your GitHub email.
Press Enter to accept the default file location.
Optionally, enter a passphrase for added security.

Step 3: Add the Key to the SSH Agent
Start the ssh-agent and add your private key to ensure authentication works seamlessly.
macOS / Linux / Git Bash:
bash
eval "$(ssh-agent -s)"
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_ed25519
(Adjust the file name if you used RSA or a different path).
Windows (PowerShell - Admin):
powershell
Get-Service -Name ssh-agent | Set-Service -StartupType Manual
Start-Service ssh-agent
ssh-add $HOME/.ssh/id_ed25519

Step 4: Add the Public Key to Your GitHub Account
Copy the content of your public key (~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub) to your clipboard. You can use pbcopy (macOS), clip (Windows), or xclip (Linux).
xclip -selection clipboard < $HOME/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub

Log in to GitHub and go to Settings > SSH and GPG keys.
Click New SSH key, add a descriptive title, paste your key, and click Add SSH key.

Step 5: Test Your SSH Connection
Run ssh -T git@github.com in your terminal. If you see a warning about host authenticity, type yes. A successful message will confirm your username.

XCLIP:
xclip is a Linux command-line utility that acts as an interface to X11 clipboard selections, allowing you to copy, paste, and pipe data between terminal commands and GUI applications.
It is commonly used to copy file contents (xclip -sel c file.txt) or terminal output (ls | xclip -sel c) directly to the clipboard.
sudo apt install xclip

